<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-12-17T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-12-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="847" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d847">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 841.731/140</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Page</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <dateline>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="italic">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-12-17">
                                <hi rend="italic">December 17, 1914</hi>.</date>
                            <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 7:30 p.m.</hi>] </dateline>
                        <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                        <p>Your 614, November 24, censorship of commercial cables.<note n="1" xml:id="d847fn1">Not printed.</note> British Government informs me
                            that arrangements are being made to allow the use of Meyer’s Atlantic
                            cotton code, 39th edition, in foreign telegrams and that a public
                            announcement on the subject will be made as soon as the date of the
                            admission of the code is settled. It is not at present practicable to
                            allow the use of more than one cotton code and British Government are
                            informed that the 39th edition of Meyer’s code is the one most generally
                            used.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Ambassador</hi>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>